<HEADLINE>
LANTERN FESTIVAL CELEBRATIONS KICK OFF
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, Feb. 28 (CNA) 02/28/07  20:52:04 (By T.C. Jiang)
</P>
<P>
Cities and counties around Taiwan will kick off various
activities this week to mark the Lantern Festival, which falls on
March 4 this year, a Tourism Bureau official announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Taipei city government took the lead Tuesday by lighting up a
"lantern tunnel" on Renai Road. Starting from March 3, colorful
lanterns will be on display at the Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city government will give away 60,000 small
lanterns to the public at the hall from March 2-4.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Taipei county government kicked off celebrations
Wednesday by launching the 2007 Pingsi Heavenly Lantern Festival,
during which sky lanterns will be released.
</P>
<P>
The official 2007 Taiwan Lantern Festival, organized by the
Tourism Bureau and the Chiayi county government, will take place
in the southern county March 3, a bureau official said.
</P>
<P>
The event, which will feature performances by Japanese and
Taiwanese music and dance groups, is expected to attract over 6
million visitors, the official said, adding that a total of
45,000 small lanterns will be distributed from March 3-5 at the
event.
</P>
<P>
The Koahsiung city government will kick off the Kaohsiung Lantern
Festival March 3, the official said, adding that the annual event
will also help promote the 2009 World Games, which the southern
port city will host.
</P>
<P>
In Taitung, eastern Taiwan, the county government will hold the
Blasting Handan parade, during which locals use firecrackers to
bombard a man who plays the part of Handan, the god of wealth.
</P>
<P>
In southern Taiwan, the Tainan county government will hold the
Yanshuei Beehive Firecracker Festival, during which the county
government will set off a 13-km- long string of firecrackers in
an attempt to break a Guinness world record.
</P>
